        <h2> Summary of Ph </h2>
          Ph is defined as how acidic or basic a solution is. It is measured on a scale
          of 14 where 7 and below is acidic solutions, and 7 and up is basic solutions
          (7 is a neutral solution water mainly). Ph is not only measured by the equation above
          but also by the number of hydronium ions (H<sup>+</sup>) and the number of hydroxyl ions
          (OH<sup>-</sup>). The more hydronium ions their are the more acidic a solution is and the more
          hydroxyl ions there are the more basic the solution is. Ph can very useful for scientists who want
          the chemical behavior of a certain substance. Ph can also be very useful in our body. For example
          our blood has a ph of 7.4 pretty neutral. When it becomes more acidic you get a condition
          known as acidosis where your blood is very acidic. This leads to hysteria, and eventually seizures. This
          acidic blood impairs the lungs and that means it retains more CO<sub>2</sub>.</article>
        <br></br>
        <p> Another example I would like to give is the enzymes in our body. We have many diffrent enzymes in our body
        that can be used for digesting foods we eat or for speeding up chemical reactions that happen in our body.They are vital
        in our body and the intresting thing is Ph plays a massive role in their functions. Pepsin (C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>6</sub>
        Cl<sub>6</sub>) is one such enzyme that is used as a stomach enzyme to help digest proteins found in food. Intrestingly enough
        its optimal Ph for reactions hoevers around 2 which is very acidic. If it was not acidic your stomach would not be able to denaturate
        proteins and though it is cliche, you would die. Another enzyme would be salivary amylase, a much more complex molecule. It has a single
        polypeptide chain with a calcium ion (Ca<sup>2+</sup>) and three water molecules. It is the primary enzyme in saliva, and helps break down
        carbohydrates into smaller sugars. The optimal ph for this emzyme would be roughly 6.7 rounded up to 7. The last example I would like like
        to bring up is akaline phosophatase. It has 5 cysteine residues, two zinc atoms, and one magnesium atoms. It is an enzyme that is used in the liver
        and most bones in the body. Its optimal ph is very basic and it is 8-10. Below is a crude drawing of the enzymes ph over time.</p>
